WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.750 --> 00:00:02.020
All right.

00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:03.450
Good morning.

00:00:03.450 --> 00:00:05.700
The subject of today's
lecture is options.

00:00:08.610 --> 00:00:13.990
And I think, maybe I'd better
first define what an option

00:00:13.990 --> 00:00:20.140
is, before I move to say
anything about them.

00:00:20.140 --> 00:00:22.579
Because some of you may not have
encountered them, because

00:00:22.579 --> 00:00:26.840
they're not part of everyday
life for most people, although

00:00:26.840 --> 00:00:28.010
they are, in a sense.

00:00:28.010 --> 00:00:29.100
I'll get back to that.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:31.535
Let me just define
the term here.

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:47.920
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:52.090
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: So
there's two kinds of options.

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:58.040
There's a call and a put, OK?

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:05.440
A call option is an option to
buy something at a specified

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:15.430
price, and the price is called
the ''exercise price'' or

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:20.660
''strike price.'' Those
are synonyms.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:26.160
And a put option is the right
to sell something at the

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:30.290
specified exercise price.

00:01:30.290 --> 00:01:40.170
And it has another term it has
to be specified, and that's

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:41.890
the exercise date.

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:52.370
OK.

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:57.030
Options go back thousands
of years.

00:01:57.030 --> 00:02:02.230
It must have happened before we
have any recorded records.

00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:07.510
If you're thinking of buying
something from someone, but

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:11.100
you don't want to put up the
money today, you go to some

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:15.010
lawyer, and say, write
up a contract.

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:18.060
I want to buy an option
to buy this thing.

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.530
So, for example, if you are
thinking of building a

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:28.670
building on land that is owned
now by a farmer, but you're

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:30.650
not ready to do it.

00:02:30.650 --> 00:02:34.030
You may be thinking about it.

00:02:34.030 --> 00:02:37.550
You can go to the farmer and
say, I'd like to buy that

00:02:37.550 --> 00:02:41.100
corner of that acre there.

00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:42.250
I'd like to have the
right to buy it.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:44.260
I'll pay you now
for the right.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.690
And you get a lawyer and you
write up a contract.

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:49.190
And that's an option.

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:55.530
You have an option to buy at the
exercise price until the

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:58.900
exercise date.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:06.930
Now, in modern terminology,
we have two kinds,

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:09.660
American and European.

00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:19.570
It doesn't refer to geography,
those two terms. The terms

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:25.810
refer, instead, to when
you can exercise.

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:28.540
So, the American option is
better than the European

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:32.420
option for the buyer, because
the American option can be

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:37.970
exercised at any time until
the exercise date.

00:03:37.970 --> 00:03:42.520
Whereas the European option can
be exercised only on the

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:44.230
exercise date.

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:48.770
But you see the American option
has to be better, or

00:03:48.770 --> 00:03:50.070
not worse than --

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:51.570
I don't know if it's strictly
better -- but not worse than

00:03:51.570 --> 00:03:53.835
the European option, because
you have more options.

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:05.160
I think, we've defined
what they are.

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:09.149
Do you understand well
enough what they are?

00:04:09.149 --> 00:04:11.680
They occur naturally in life.

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:17.380
I remember, Avinash Dixit was
writing about options and he

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.570
said, well, when you're dating
someone and you know the

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:24.030
person will marry you, you have
an option that you can

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:30.100
exercise at any time by
agreeing to marry.

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:33.750
Now, one of the theorems in
option theory is, you usually

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:38.010
don't want to exercise
a call option early.

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:44.950
And so, Dixit would say, well,
maybe that's why a lot of

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:47.220
people have trouble
getting married.

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:50.770
They don't want to exercise
their option early.

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:53.680
What we'll see is that options
have option value.

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.690
They give you a choice, and so
there's something there.

00:04:56.690 --> 00:04:59.080
When you exercise an option,
that is, when you actually buy

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:03.140
the thing, or in the case of
a put, sell the thing, then

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:04.740
you're losing the choice.

00:05:04.740 --> 00:05:06.275
So, you've given up something.

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:12.980
Of course, you have to also
exercise eventually, if things

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:14.765
are going to make sense.

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:20.440
Usually, when we talk about
options, we're talking now

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:23.720
about options to buy a share
of stock, or 100 shares of

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:28.010
stock, and that's the
usual example.

00:05:28.010 --> 00:05:31.800
But they occur all
over the place.

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:37.550
Let me mention some other
examples of options.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:39.930
The usual story is
the stock option.

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:44.500
You go to your broker and you
say, I'd like to buy an option

00:05:44.500 --> 00:05:47.790
to buy 100 shares
of Microsoft.

00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:51.140
I don't want to buy Microsoft, I
want to buy an option to buy

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:55.800
Microsoft, which happens to be
cheaper, by the way, usually.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:00.560
Usually, it costs more money to
actually buy the thing than

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:03.250
to buy the right to buy the
thing at another price.

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:05.810
We'll get back to that.

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:10.800
But in a sense, let's think
about this, stocks themselves

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:17.210
are options in a sense, with
a zero exercise price.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:19.730
Maybe, I'll have to get
back and explain, but

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:22.220
what I mean is --

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:29.130
let me get back and explain
that in a minute.

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:32.530
But let me go ahead to other
examples, mortgages.

00:06:32.530 --> 00:06:36.890
An ordinary home mortgage has
an option characteristic to

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:42.690
it, in the sense that, if the
price of your home drops a

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:48.880
lot, you can just walk away from
the mortgage, and say,

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:49.470
I'm out of here.

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:52.430
It's like not exercising
an option.

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:55.120
It's analogous.

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:58.480
Or I can choose to prepay a
mortgage early, and that's

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:00.145
like exercising an option.

00:07:00.145 --> 00:07:04.430
So, option pricing gets into
all sorts of things.

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:09.220
OK.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.700
I thought I should say something
about the purposes

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:25.550
of options, before I move on to
try to discuss what their

00:07:25.550 --> 00:07:28.640
properties and pricing are,
which is the main subject of

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:30.200
this lecture.

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:42.200
I can give two different
justifications for options.

00:07:42.200 --> 00:07:45.250
Why do we have options?

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:47.180
Some people cynically think
that options are

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:49.352
just gambling vehicles.

00:07:49.352 --> 00:07:50.650
It's another way to gamble.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:53.650
You can go to the casino,
you can play poker,

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.940
or you can buy options.

00:07:55.940 --> 00:07:59.440
Well, I think for some people
that's just what it is, the

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:02.090
volatile risky investments
that can make

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:03.710
you a lot of money.

00:08:03.710 --> 00:08:10.890
But I think, they have a basic
purpose, or purposes.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:15.064
First of all, theoretical.

00:08:15.064 --> 00:08:20.360
If we were trying to design the
ideal financial system,

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:21.610
what would we do?

00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:34.179
Some people thought of ideal
economic systems without

00:08:34.179 --> 00:08:36.970
reference to finance,
like Karl Marx --

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:39.750
I come back to him -- the great
communist, who thought

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:43.410
that we would have an ideal
communist state and there'd be

00:08:43.410 --> 00:08:44.760
no financial markets.

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:50.500
When they actually tried it
and they tried to do it, I

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:55.150
think they gradually realized
that not having any financial

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:59.960
markets makes our
entrepreneurship, our

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:03.380
management of enterprises,
kind of blind.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:05.050
We can't see, where we're going

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:06.500
because there's no prices.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:09.590
We don't know what anything
is worth.

00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:13.730
There was an old joke that the
communist countries survived

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:16.830
only because they had prices
from capitalist

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:18.530
countries to rely on.

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:22.590
Otherwise, they don't know
anything about values or

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:24.820
profits, right?

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:26.070
So, we need prices.

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:34.090
Many people have written about
this, but I mentioned, in

00:09:34.090 --> 00:09:42.810
1964, Kenneth Arrow, who is an
economic theorist, wrote a

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:48.290
classic paper, in which he
argued that, unless we have

00:09:48.290 --> 00:09:52.940
prices for all states of nature,
there's a sense in

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:56.270
which the economic system
is inefficient.

00:09:56.270 --> 00:10:00.490
You really need the price of
everything, including the

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:03.440
price of some possibility.

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:10.240
In a sense, that's what options
are giving you, the

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:14.710
existence of options
is giving you.

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:22.680
So, Steven Ross, who used to
teach here at Yale, a friend

00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:31.090
of mine, lives here in New
Haven, in 1976, in The

00:10:31.090 --> 00:10:34.490
Quarterly Journal of Economics,
wrote a classic

00:10:34.490 --> 00:10:39.500
paper about options, showing
that, in a sense, they

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:41.930
complete the state space.

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:48.850
They create prices for
everything that affects

00:10:48.850 --> 00:10:50.460
decision-making.

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:52.720
I'm not going to get into the
technicalities of the paper,

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.670
but I wanted to start with a
theoretical justification for

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.090
options, so you'll see
why we're doing this.

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:01.240
I don't want this to come across
as a lecture, on how

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:03.690
you can gamble in the
options market.

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:07.660
This is about making things work
right for the economic

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:10.840
system, improving
human welfare.

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.510
But a lot of people
don't get that.

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:16.920
That's why Karl Marx
was so successful.

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:18.400
It seems too abstract.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:20.530
What does this options
market do for us?

00:11:23.530 --> 00:11:26.160
Let me just go back to the
example I started out with.

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:28.410
You're a construction firm,
and you're thinking of

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:31.280
building something, a new
supermarket, where people can

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:32.550
buy their food.

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:37.880
And you note that there's a pair
of expressways crossing

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:40.320
somewhere, and you think, that's
the perfect place to

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:42.970
build a mega supermarket,
because everyone can

00:11:42.970 --> 00:11:45.100
get there by car.

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:47.320
And there's a lot of land,
I can build a big

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:50.060
parking lot, perfect.

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:53.390
But before you think further,
you go to buy an option on the

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:54.700
land, right?

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:57.080
So, you knock on the door at the
farmhouse, and there's a

00:11:57.080 --> 00:12:00.700
farmer with all these acres, and
you say, I'm thinking of

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:03.340
building a mega supermarket
here.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:06.520
I'd like to buy an option
on your farm.

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:08.650
You learn something
at that moment.

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:11.950
You might learn that the farmer
says, I've already sold

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:15.220
an option, so I can't do it.

00:12:15.220 --> 00:12:17.670
You could try to talk to the
person I sold it to, and see

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:20.390
if you can buy it from him.

00:12:20.390 --> 00:12:23.190
Or the farmer might say, I've
had three other offers, and

00:12:23.190 --> 00:12:26.320
I'm raising my price
to some millions

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.750
and millions of dollars.

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.850
Then, you have second thoughts
about doing it.

00:12:30.850 --> 00:12:32.250
You see what I'm saying,
that the price

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:33.490
discovery is in there?

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:35.930
It's making things happen
differently.

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:37.570
You're learning something.

00:12:37.570 --> 00:12:39.510
The farmer is learning
something.

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:42.440
You are learning something from
the options market, and

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:47.390
ultimately it decides where
that supermarket will go.

00:12:47.390 --> 00:12:50.880
So, that's the theoretical
purpose of options.

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:55.560
I wanted to talk, also, about a

00:12:55.560 --> 00:13:02.590
behavioral purpose of options.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:09.850
It's a little fuzzier about the
actual benefits of options

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:15.010
from this standpoint.

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:24.350
The behavioral theory of
options says that --

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:27.720
Very many different aspects
of human behavior tie into

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:36.970
options, but I would say it
has something to do with

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:41.520
attention anomalies
and salience.

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:48.330
Psychologists talk about this,
that people make mistakes very

00:13:48.330 --> 00:13:52.180
commonly in what they pay
attention to, what strikes the

00:13:52.180 --> 00:13:54.450
fancy of their imagination.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:57.390
Salience is something
psychologists also talk about.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:07.290
Salient events are events that
tend to attract attention,

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:08.540
tend to be remembered.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:15.960
Now, when you think of options,
a lot of options are

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:19.670
what are called incentive
options, OK?

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:26.450
And when you get your first job,
you may discover this.

00:14:26.450 --> 00:14:28.310
They'll give you options
to buy shares in the

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:30.210
company you work for.

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:32.470
Why do they do that?

00:14:32.470 --> 00:14:35.370
I think it's because of certain
human behavioral

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:38.430
traits that I mention
here, your

00:14:38.430 --> 00:14:41.260
attention and your salience.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:44.040
It's not necessarily very
expensive for a company to

00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:49.300
give you options to buy shares
in the company, but it puts

00:14:49.300 --> 00:14:52.420
you in a situation, where you
start to pay attention to the

00:14:52.420 --> 00:14:53.870
value of the company.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:57.150
It becomes salient for you, and
you start hoping that the

00:14:57.150 --> 00:14:59.630
price of the company will go up,
because you have options

00:14:59.630 --> 00:15:02.190
to buy it, at a strike price.

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:05.560
You hope that the company's
price per share goes above

00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:07.170
your strike price,
because then your

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:08.340
options are worth something.

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:11.190
They're in the money.

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:14.140
So, it may change your
motivation and your morale at

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:16.680
work, or sense of identity
with the company.

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:20.420
All these sorts of
things figure in.

00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:23.140
That's why we have incentive
options.

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:30.020
They can also give you
peace of mind.

00:15:38.890 --> 00:15:43.170
Insurance is actually related to
options in the sense that,

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:46.570
when you buy insurance on your
house, it's like buying a put

00:15:46.570 --> 00:15:49.540
option on your house, although
it may be not directly

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:52.660
connected to the home's
value, right?

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:55.600
When you buy an insurance policy
in your house, and the

00:15:55.600 --> 00:15:59.880
house burns down, you collect
on the insurance policy.

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.310
Well, the price of your
house fell to zero.

00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:04.510
If you had bought a put option
on the house, it would do the

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:05.940
same thing, right?

00:16:05.940 --> 00:16:10.040
You would have an option to
sell it at a high price on

00:16:10.040 --> 00:16:12.160
something that's
now worthless.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:17.020
So, insurance is like options,
and insurance gives

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:19.910
you peace of mind.

00:16:19.910 --> 00:16:24.040
So, people think in certain
repetitive patterns, and one

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:28.080
of them is, that I would like to
not worry about something.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:32.800
So, I can get peace of mind,
if I have a put option on

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:36.520
something that I might otherwise
worry about.

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:39.860
All right, maybe that's enough
of an introduction, but I'm

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:42.230
giving you both theoretical
reasons for options and

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:44.530
behavioral reasons.

00:16:44.530 --> 00:16:46.805
I think of them as basically
inevitable.

00:16:49.430 --> 00:16:52.490
You may have people advising
you not to bother

00:16:52.490 --> 00:16:54.220
with options markets.

00:16:54.220 --> 00:16:59.290
That might be right for you, in
a sense, but I think that

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:01.750
they're always going to be with
us, and so it's something

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.000
that we have to understand.

