00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:44.710
But if it's a stock, someone
can write an option, who

00:22:44.710 --> 00:22:46.170
doesn't even own the stock.

00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:50.055
And so, that's called a naked
seller of an option, OK?

00:22:52.670 --> 00:22:54.620
Neither the buyer nor the
seller ever have to

00:22:54.620 --> 00:22:55.450
trade in the stock.

00:22:55.450 --> 00:22:58.390
This is a market by itself.

00:22:58.390 --> 00:23:01.870
You could buy an option, and
then you could sell it as an

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:04.280
option without ever
exercising it.

00:23:07.550 --> 00:23:11.660
The writer could write an
option, and then buy an option

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:14.360
to cancel it out later, and
then, essentially, get out of

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:15.470
that contract.

00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:19.690
So, the option becomes a market
of its own, where

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.390
prices of options start to
look like an independent

00:23:23.390 --> 00:23:26.475
market, and this is called
a derivatives market.

00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:36.560
There's an underlying stock
price, but this is a

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:38.250
derivative of the stock price.

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:49.080
The first options exchange was
the Chicago Board Options

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:55.000
Exchange, which came
in in 1973.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.570
Before that, options were
traded, but they were traded

00:23:58.570 --> 00:24:02.150
through brokers and they didn't
have the same presence.

00:24:02.150 --> 00:24:05.640
You didn't see all these options
prices in newspapers.

00:24:05.640 --> 00:24:09.840
It's when they opened the market
for options, that the

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:12.150
options trading became
a big thing.

00:24:12.150 --> 00:24:16.040
So, options markets are
relatively new, if you

00:24:16.040 --> 00:24:17.990
consider '73 new.

00:24:17.990 --> 00:24:20.090
You weren't born then.

00:24:20.090 --> 00:24:23.570
It's not really that long ago.

00:24:23.570 --> 00:24:28.300
Since then, there are many more
options exchanges, but

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.100
CBOE is the first one.

00:24:30.100 --> 00:24:33.010
They're now all over
the world.

00:24:33.010 --> 00:24:37.860
And we also have options
on futures.

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:41.750
And so, futures exchanges now
routinely trade options on

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:44.560
their futures contracts.

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:49.800
So, that's a derivative on a
derivative, but it's done.

00:24:54.980 --> 00:24:59.710
So, let me draw a simple picture
of option pricing.

00:24:59.710 --> 00:25:11.410
So, this is the stock price
and this is the

00:25:11.410 --> 00:25:19.900
option price, OK?

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:23.610
And I'm going to mark here,
the exercise price.

00:25:32.310 --> 00:25:37.620
Let's look at the exercise
date, the last day.

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:43.110
The option is about to expire,
and this is your last chance

00:25:43.110 --> 00:25:44.090
to buy the stock.

00:25:44.090 --> 00:25:46.070
Then, it doesn't matter, on
that day, whether it's an

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:47.610
American or European option.

00:25:47.610 --> 00:25:50.300
They're both the same
on the last day.

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:53.230
What is the price of the option
as a function of the

00:25:53.230 --> 00:25:55.060
stock price?

00:25:55.060 --> 00:25:59.460
Well, if the stock price is less
than the exercise price,

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.870
the option is worthless,
right?

00:26:02.870 --> 00:26:04.970
It will not be exercised.

00:26:04.970 --> 00:26:09.010
You won't exercise an option
to buy it for more than you

00:26:09.010 --> 00:26:10.290
could just buy it on
the market, right?

00:26:10.290 --> 00:26:12.780
STUDENT: You have
to say ''call''.

