00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:22.560
Thank you.

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:30.370
But if it's above the exercise
price, this is a 45 degree

00:26:30.370 --> 00:26:34.570
angle, that's a line with the
slope of one, the option

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:37.870
prices rises with the stock.

00:26:37.870 --> 00:26:41.270
In fact, it just equals the
stock price minus the exercise

00:26:41.270 --> 00:26:42.990
price, right?

00:26:42.990 --> 00:26:47.170
So, this region, we say, is
''out of the money.'' The

00:26:47.170 --> 00:26:52.569
option is out of the money,
when its prices

00:26:52.569 --> 00:26:54.300
[clarification: the stock
price], for a call, is less

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:55.860
than the exercise price.

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:58.490
Here, it's ''in the money.''
I'll put it up

00:26:58.490 --> 00:26:59.740
here, in the money.

00:27:02.330 --> 00:27:05.050
And then, on the exercise date,
it will always equal the

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:08.410
stock price minus the
exercise price.

00:27:08.410 --> 00:27:10.230
So, it's very simple.

00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:13.970
Now, one confusion that's often
made: I gave the example

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:18.200
of building a shopping center
or a supermarket on a farm.

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:21.330
Now, someone might think that
you buy an option on it, so

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.650
that you can think about it and
make up your mind later.

00:27:24.650 --> 00:27:27.030
Well, in a sense, you
could do that.

00:27:27.030 --> 00:27:31.070
But the thing is, you will
exercise the option whether or

00:27:31.070 --> 00:27:34.870
not you build the shopping mall
or this supermarket, if

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:36.810
it's in the money, right?

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:39.960
Suppose, you changed your mind,
and I don't want to

00:27:39.960 --> 00:27:41.360
build the supermarket.

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:45.330
But I'm sitting on an option
that I bought, to buy his land

00:27:45.330 --> 00:27:48.900
for a price, which is less than
the market price for it.

00:27:48.900 --> 00:27:50.410
Of course, I'll buy it.

00:27:50.410 --> 00:27:52.660
So, you're going to buy it,
whether you build the shopping

00:27:52.660 --> 00:27:55.030
center or not.

00:27:55.030 --> 00:27:57.660
You always exercise the option,
if it's in the money

00:27:57.660 --> 00:27:58.400
on the last day.

00:27:58.400 --> 00:27:59.610
That's the assumption.

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.590
I mean you could not, I suppose,
if you like the

00:28:01.590 --> 00:28:03.610
farmer and you want
to be a nice guy.

00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:04.630
I don't know.

00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:11.730
But usually, what it is, it's a
non-linear relation between

00:28:11.730 --> 00:28:13.940
the stock price and
the derivative.

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:20.020
So, the derivative is a broken
straight line function of the

00:28:20.020 --> 00:28:20.890
stock price.

00:28:20.890 --> 00:28:24.290
Whereas all the portfolios
we construct, are linear.

00:28:24.290 --> 00:28:25.160
They're straight lines.

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:26.790
They don't have a
break in them.

00:28:26.790 --> 00:28:30.834
So, the option creates a break
in the function of

00:28:30.834 --> 00:28:33.130
the stock price --

00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:35.670
and this is why Ross emphasized
that options price

00:28:35.670 --> 00:28:37.880
something very different,
that's not priced

00:28:37.880 --> 00:28:39.060
in the regular --

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:45.380
no portfolio shows you this
broken straight line relation.

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:47.530
Now, I wanted to then
talk about a put.

00:28:47.530 --> 00:28:49.050
What is a put?

00:28:49.050 --> 00:28:51.640
Let me erase, where it says
in and out of the money.

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:54.550
I'll show it.

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:59.290
I'll do this with a dashed line,
so that you'll see which

00:28:59.290 --> 00:28:59.650
one is which --

00:28:59.650 --> 00:29:01.470
I'm leaving the call line up.

00:29:01.470 --> 00:29:04.215
With a put, a put is out
of the money up here --

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:10.620
I can't really show
it too well --

00:29:10.620 --> 00:29:16.340
if the stock price is above the
exercise price, because

00:29:16.340 --> 00:29:17.660
you're selling now.

00:29:17.660 --> 00:29:23.150
And it's in the money, if the
stock price is less than the

00:29:23.150 --> 00:29:24.280
exercise price --

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:25.670
I didn't draw that very well.

00:29:25.670 --> 00:29:28.820
That's supposed to be
a 45 degree line.

00:29:28.820 --> 00:29:32.825
That's a 45 degree angle, has
a slope of minus one, right?

00:29:32.825 --> 00:29:34.075
That's on the exercise date.

00:29:41.980 --> 00:29:44.730
Now, it's interesting that
there's a pretty simple

00:29:44.730 --> 00:29:48.900
pattern here between
puts and calls.

00:29:48.900 --> 00:29:56.160
What if I buy one call and I
short one put, all right?

00:29:56.160 --> 00:30:00.070
Or write a put, writing a put
and shorting a put are the

00:30:00.070 --> 00:30:03.140
same thing, all right?

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:06.730
What does that portfolio
look like?

00:30:06.730 --> 00:30:15.700
Well, if I put that portfolio
together, I want to have plus

00:30:15.700 --> 00:30:20.860
one call minus one
put, all right?

00:30:20.860 --> 00:30:28.500
My portfolio relation to the
stock price is going to look

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:29.290
like that, right?

00:30:29.290 --> 00:30:30.540
It's just going to be
a straight line.

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:39.710
So, the value of my portfolio
is equal to the stock price

00:30:39.710 --> 00:30:41.350
minus the exercise price.

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:43.220
Simple as that.

00:30:43.220 --> 00:30:48.290
And my portfolio can be negative
now, because I've

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:49.110
shorted something.

00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:51.410
I can have a negative
portfolio value.

00:30:55.310 --> 00:30:58.520
That's very simple,
can you see that?

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:04.415
This leads us to the put-call
parity equation.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:11.260
If a put minus a call
[correction: a call minus a

00:31:11.260 --> 00:31:13.840
put] is the same thing as the
stock minus the exercise

00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:18.480
price, then the prices should
add up too, right?

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:21.600
So, put-call parity --

00:31:26.560 --> 00:31:29.120
there's different ways
of writing this.

00:31:29.120 --> 00:31:46.490
But it says that the stock price
equals the call price

00:31:46.490 --> 00:31:58.080
minus put price plus exercise
price on the last day, on the

00:31:58.080 --> 00:31:59.270
exercise day, right?

00:31:59.270 --> 00:32:00.520
It's simple.

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:06.160
This is put-call parity
on the exercise date.

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:16.420
Now, let's think about some day
before the exercise date.

00:32:16.420 --> 00:32:17.700
Well, you know this is
going to happen on

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.210
the exercise date.

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:23.320
So, at any date before the
exercise date, the same thing

00:32:23.320 --> 00:32:26.810
should hold, except that
we've got to make

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:30.200
this the present value.

00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:34.890
Present discounted value
of the exercise price.

00:32:34.890 --> 00:32:38.580
And also we have to add in, in
case there is any dividends

00:32:38.580 --> 00:32:42.060
paid between now and the
exercise date, plus the

00:32:42.060 --> 00:32:49.150
present discounted value of
dividends paid between now and

00:32:49.150 --> 00:32:50.570
the exercise date.

00:32:50.570 --> 00:32:52.145
Because the stock gets
that, and the option

00:32:52.145 --> 00:32:54.480
holders don't, OK?

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:58.790
So, that's called the put-call
parity relation.

00:32:58.790 --> 00:33:01.780
And now I can cross out
''exercise date.'' This should

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:05.600
hold on all dates.

00:33:05.600 --> 00:33:08.640
Because if it didn't hold, there
would be an arbitrage,

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.430
or profit opportunity.

00:33:11.430 --> 00:33:17.990
So, it should hold on this
page, except for minor

00:33:17.990 --> 00:33:21.620
failures to hold.

00:33:21.620 --> 00:33:23.710
It should hold approximately
on this page.

00:33:23.710 --> 00:33:25.750
And let me give you
one example.

00:33:25.750 --> 00:33:28.260
See, if it holds.

00:33:28.260 --> 00:33:32.390
Let's consider the one
that I can reach.

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:35.790
OK, oh, this is the
stock price.

00:33:35.790 --> 00:33:36.970
So, what do I have?

00:33:36.970 --> 00:33:43.890
The biggest thing here is the
strike price, exercise price.

00:33:43.890 --> 00:33:45.140
So, we want to do --

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:56.530
we'll do this line, $25.00 plus
$0.45 minus $3.50, and

00:33:56.530 --> 00:33:58.040
I'm assuming there's
no dividend paid

00:33:58.040 --> 00:34:01.152
between now and May.

00:34:01.152 --> 00:34:04.030
It comes out very
close to $21.85.

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:06.449
I can't do the arithmetic
in my head.

00:34:06.449 --> 00:34:10.540
It may not hold exactly, because
these prices may not

00:34:10.540 --> 00:34:13.050
all have been quoted at exactly
the same time, and

00:34:13.050 --> 00:34:18.330
there's some transactional
costs that limit this.

00:34:18.330 --> 00:34:19.210
Do you see that?

00:34:19.210 --> 00:34:22.755
So, because of the put-call
parity relation, The Wall

00:34:22.755 --> 00:34:26.570
Street Journal didn't even
bother to put the put prices

00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:29.989
in, because you can get
one from the other.

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:35.480
But they do put them in, just
because people like to see

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:42.139
them, and some people might be
trying to profit from the

00:34:42.139 --> 00:34:45.110
put-call parity arbitrage.

00:34:45.110 --> 00:34:48.970
But for our purposes, we only
have to do call pricing.

00:34:48.970 --> 00:34:51.870
Once we've got call pricing,
we've got put prices.

00:34:51.870 --> 00:34:54.950
So, I just use the put-call
parity relation and I get put

00:34:54.950 --> 00:34:56.440
price prices.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:58.930
So, now let's think about
how you would price puts

00:34:58.930 --> 00:35:02.220
[correction: calls].

00:35:02.220 --> 00:35:08.220
The price of a put
[correction: call],

00:35:08.220 --> 00:35:11.050
we know what it is on the
exercise date, right?

00:35:11.050 --> 00:35:13.700
I'm going to forget
the dashed lines.

00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:15.760
There's no dashed lines
here anymore.

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:18.132
We're just talking about
call prices.

00:35:18.132 --> 00:35:28.060
All right, so this shows
the price of a put on

00:35:28.060 --> 00:35:29.850
the last day --

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:32.430
of a call on the last day.

00:35:32.430 --> 00:35:35.390
Now, what about an
earlier day?

00:35:35.390 --> 00:35:35.530
[clarification: The following
argument about price bounds

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:35.630
solely applies to
call options.

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:35.790
It also abstracts from dividend
payments of the

00:35:35.790 --> 00:35:37.040
underlying stock.]

00:35:39.350 --> 00:35:43.870
Well, the price of a call can
never be negative, right?

00:35:43.870 --> 00:35:46.680
So, the call price has to
be above this line.

00:35:49.690 --> 00:35:55.090
It can never be worth less than
the stock price minus the

00:35:55.090 --> 00:36:02.480
exercise price, even before
the exercise date.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:04.180
And also, it can't be
worth more than

00:36:04.180 --> 00:36:05.430
the stock price itself.

00:36:05.430 --> 00:36:07.440
I'll draw a 45 degree line
from the origin.

00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:17.310
That's supposed to be
parallels of that.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:22.060
It's obvious that the call price
has to be above this

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:25.910
broken straight line, but
not too far above it.

00:36:25.910 --> 00:36:28.990
Above this broken straight line,
representing the price

00:36:28.990 --> 00:36:31.670
as a function of the stock
price on the last day.

00:36:31.670 --> 00:36:35.420
And the closer you get to the
last day, the closer the

00:36:35.420 --> 00:36:37.770
options price will get
to that curve.

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:44.830
So, on some day before the
exercise date, the call option

00:36:44.830 --> 00:36:49.910
price will probably look
something like that, right?

00:36:49.910 --> 00:36:55.850
It's above the broken straight
line because of option value.

00:36:55.850 --> 00:36:59.390
So, think it this way, suppose
an option is out of

00:36:59.390 --> 00:37:01.780
the money today --

00:37:01.780 --> 00:37:03.405
well, you can see out of
the money options.

00:37:06.840 --> 00:37:09.840
For a call, this is out
of the money, right?

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:14.700
Because its stock price is
$21.85, but I've got an option

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:16.960
to buy it for $25.00.

00:37:16.960 --> 00:37:19.540
All right, that's going to be
worthless, unless the option

00:37:19.540 --> 00:37:19.830
price [correction: stock price]

00:37:19.830 --> 00:37:23.840
goes up before it expires.

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:26.410
So, it's only worth something,
because there's a chance that

00:37:26.410 --> 00:37:30.830
it will be worth something
on the exercise date.

00:37:30.830 --> 00:37:33.070
And what are people paying
for that chance?

00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:35.980
$0.45, not much.

00:37:35.980 --> 00:37:37.390
Why are they paying so little?

00:37:37.390 --> 00:37:42.070
Well, you can say intuitively,
it's because it's pretty far.

00:37:42.070 --> 00:37:47.510
$21.85 is pretty far from
$25.00, and this option only

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:48.550
has a month to go.

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:51.460
What's the chance that the price
will go up that much?

00:37:51.460 --> 00:37:53.680
Well, there is a chance,
but it's not that big.

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:56.530
So, I'm only willing
to pay $0.45 to buy

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:58.800
an option like that.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:02.150
So, we're somewhere like
here on that row

00:38:02.150 --> 00:38:03.400
that I've shown you.

00:38:07.200 --> 00:38:10.860
The reason you don't want to
exercise an option early is,

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:16.460
because, if you exercise it
early, your value drops down

00:38:16.460 --> 00:38:19.640
to the broken straight
line, right?

00:38:19.640 --> 00:38:23.630
It's always worth more than
the broken straight line

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:26.620
indicates before the
exercise date.

00:38:26.620 --> 00:38:30.190
So, if you want to get your
money out, sell the option.

00:38:30.190 --> 00:38:32.100
Don't exercise it early.

00:38:32.100 --> 00:38:35.300
So, that's why the distinction
between European and American

00:38:35.300 --> 00:38:40.450
options is not as big or as
important as you might think,

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:40.660
at first. [clarification:
American call options should

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:40.710
indeed not be exercised early.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:40.780
However, there are circumstances
under which it

00:38:40.780 --> 00:38:42.030
is optimal to exercise an
American put option early.]

00:38:42.030 --> 00:38:53.180
So, we can just price European
options, and then we can infer

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:56.400
what other options would
be, what put

00:38:56.400 --> 00:38:57.650
options would be worth.

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:10.390
Let's now talk about
pricing of options.

00:39:10.390 --> 00:39:14.490
And the main pricing equation
that we're going to use is the

00:39:14.490 --> 00:39:17.640
Black-Scholes Option
Pricing equation.

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:20.930
But, before that, I wanted to
just give you a simple story

00:39:20.930 --> 00:39:23.550
of options pricing, just
to give you some

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:26.930
idea, how it works.

00:39:26.930 --> 00:39:29.150
And then I'm going to not
actually derive the

00:39:29.150 --> 00:39:34.580
Black-Scholes formula, but I'm
going to show it to you.

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:41.880
I'm going to tell you a simple
story, just to give some

00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:48.490
intuitive feel about the
pricing of options.

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:55.050
And to simplify the story, I'm
going to tell a story about a

00:39:55.050 --> 00:39:58.920
world, in which there's only
two possible prices for the

00:39:58.920 --> 00:40:00.800
underlying stock.

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:01.930
That makes it binomial.

00:40:01.930 --> 00:40:06.820
There's only two things that can
happen, and you can either

00:40:06.820 --> 00:40:10.310
be high or low, all right?

00:40:10.310 --> 00:40:12.020
So, let me get my notation.

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:19.110
I'm going to use S as the
stock price, all right?

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:26.910
I'm going to assume that the
stock price, that's today --

00:40:30.140 --> 00:40:32.950
this is also a simple world in
that there's only one day.

00:40:32.950 --> 00:40:34.380
The option expires tomorrow.

00:40:34.380 --> 00:40:36.940
There's only one more price
we're going to see.

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:40.440
So, the stock is either going
to go up or down.

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:47.260
So, u is equal to one plus the
fraction that it goes up.

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:50.390
u stands for up.

00:40:50.390 --> 00:40:55.060
And d is down, is one plus
the fraction down.

00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:05.230
So, that means that stock price
either becomes Su, which

00:41:05.230 --> 00:41:10.950
means it goes up by a fraction,
multiple u, or it is

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:15.620
Sd, which means it goes
down by a multiple d.

00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:17.250
And that's all we know, OK?

00:41:17.250 --> 00:41:22.890
But now we have a call option:
Call C the price of the call.

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:28.590
We're going to try to
derive what that is.

00:41:28.590 --> 00:41:33.670
But we know, from our broken
straight line analysis, we

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:39.910
know what C sub u is, the price
if the stock goes up.

00:41:39.910 --> 00:41:46.880
And we know what C sub d is,
it's the price if down, OK?

00:41:46.880 --> 00:42:02.240
So, suppose the option has
exercise price E, all right.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:04.160
Do you understand this world?

00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:05.820
Simple story.

00:42:05.820 --> 00:42:10.870
Now, what I want to do is
consider a portfolio of both

00:42:10.870 --> 00:42:13.947
the stock and the option,
that is riskless.

00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:24.980
I'm going to buy a number of
options equal to H. H is the

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:39.350
hedge ratio, which is the number
of shares purchased per

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:40.120
option sold.

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:44.740
So, I'm going to sell a call
option to hedge the stock

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:49.340
price, to reduce the risk
of the stock price, OK?

00:42:49.340 --> 00:42:57.720
And so, hedge ratio is shares
purchased over options.

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:01.950
Each option is to buy
one share, OK?

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:04.950
So, what I'm going to
do is, write one

00:43:04.950 --> 00:43:08.180
call and buy H shares.

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:11.940
So, let me erase this and
start over again.

00:43:17.500 --> 00:43:22.075
I'm on my way to deriving the
options price for you --

00:43:22.075 --> 00:43:23.470
a little bit of math.

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:46.780
So, I'm going to write one call
and buy H shares, OK.

00:43:46.780 --> 00:43:53.200
If the stock goes up, if we
discover we're in an up world

00:43:53.200 --> 00:44:00.600
next period, my portfolio
is worth uHS

00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:04.810
minus C sub u, right?

00:44:04.810 --> 00:44:08.370
Because the share price goes
from S to uS, and I've got H

00:44:08.370 --> 00:44:15.010
shares, and I've written
a call, so I have

00:44:15.010 --> 00:44:18.890
to pay C sub u.

00:44:18.890 --> 00:44:28.250
If it's down, then my
portfolio is dHS

00:44:28.250 --> 00:44:34.310
minus C sub d, OK?

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:37.050
This is simple enough?

00:44:37.050 --> 00:44:40.450
Now, what I want to do is
eliminate all risk.

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:44.980
So, that means I want to choose
H, so that these two

00:44:44.980 --> 00:44:46.560
numbers are the same.

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:48.550
And if I do that, I've
got a riskless

00:44:48.550 --> 00:44:51.170
investment, all right?

00:44:51.170 --> 00:44:55.860
So, set these equal
to each other.

00:44:55.860 --> 00:44:59.230
And that implies something about
H. We can drive what H

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:04.010
is, if I just put these two
equal to each other and solve

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:15.110
for H. And I get H equals C sub
u minus C sub d, all over

00:45:15.110 --> 00:45:21.990
u minus d times S, OK?

00:45:21.990 --> 00:45:25.640
So, I've been able to put
together a portfolio of the

00:45:25.640 --> 00:45:30.260
stock and the option
that has zero risk.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:34.410
If I do this, if I hold this
amount of shares in my

00:45:34.410 --> 00:45:38.770
portfolio, I've got a
riskless portfolio.

00:45:38.770 --> 00:45:43.840
So, that means that the riskless
portfolio has to earn

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:46.440
the riskless rate, right?

00:45:46.440 --> 00:45:48.752
It's the same thing as a
riskless rate [correction:

00:45:48.752 --> 00:45:49.970
same thing as a riskless
investment], so it has to earn

00:45:49.970 --> 00:45:51.130
that [clarification: earn
the riskless rate].

00:45:51.130 --> 00:45:53.940
If I can erase this now,
I'm almost there,

00:45:53.940 --> 00:45:57.000
through option pricing.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:03.935
The option pricing then says
that, since I'm derived what H

00:46:03.935 --> 00:46:10.040
is, the portfolio has to be
worth one plus the interest

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:20.140
rate times what I put in, which
is HS minus C. And that

00:46:20.140 --> 00:46:26.520
has to equal the value of the
portfolio at the end, which is

00:46:26.520 --> 00:46:35.840
either uHS minus C sub u,
or dHS minus C sub d,

00:46:35.840 --> 00:46:38.930
the same thing, OK?

00:46:41.440 --> 00:46:45.560
So, I've already derived what
H is, and I substituted into

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:54.900
that, and I solved for C. So,
substitute H in and solve for

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:59.880
C, and we get the
call price, OK?

00:46:59.880 --> 00:47:06.230
It's a little bit complicated,
but the call option price has

00:47:06.230 --> 00:47:17.310
to equal one plus r minus d,
all over u minus d, times C

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:26.540
sub u over one plus r, plus u
minus one minus r, all over u

00:47:26.540 --> 00:47:33.410
minus d, times C sub d
all over one plus r.

00:47:33.410 --> 00:47:36.870
And I'll put a box around that
because that's our option

00:47:36.870 --> 00:47:41.590
price formula, OK?

00:47:41.590 --> 00:47:45.030
Did you follow all that?

00:47:45.030 --> 00:47:47.070
This is derived --

00:47:47.070 --> 00:47:50.920
This option price formula
was derived from a

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:52.810
no arbitrage condition.

00:47:57.910 --> 00:48:04.120
Arbitrage, in finance, means
riskless profit opportunity.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:08.550
And the no arbitrage condition
says, it's never possible to

00:48:08.550 --> 00:48:13.270
make more than the riskless rate
risklessly, all right?

00:48:13.270 --> 00:48:16.330
If I could, suppose I had some
way -- suppose the riskless

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:22.870
rate is 5%, and I can make 6%
risklessly, then I will borrow

00:48:22.870 --> 00:48:27.050
at the riskless rate and put
it into the 6% opportunity.

00:48:27.050 --> 00:48:29.400
And I'll do that until
kingdom come.

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:31.150
There's no limit to how
much I'll do that.

00:48:31.150 --> 00:48:32.400
I'll do it forever.

00:48:34.800 --> 00:48:40.090
It's too much of a profit
opportunity to ever happen.

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:43.390
One of the most powerful
insights of theoretical

00:48:43.390 --> 00:48:47.190
finance is, that the
no arbitrage

00:48:47.190 --> 00:48:49.100
condition should hold.

00:48:49.100 --> 00:48:52.260
It's like saying, there are no
$10 bills on the pavement.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:55.190
When you walk down the street
and you see a $10 bill lying

00:48:55.190 --> 00:49:00.030
there on the street, your first
thought ought to be, are

00:49:00.030 --> 00:49:02.530
my eyes deceiving me?

00:49:02.530 --> 00:49:04.500
Because somebody else
would have picked it

00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:05.430
up if it were there.

00:49:05.430 --> 00:49:06.780
How can it be there?

00:49:06.780 --> 00:49:08.490
I once actually had
that experience.

00:49:08.490 --> 00:49:11.180
I was walking down the
street in New York.

00:49:11.180 --> 00:49:13.000
It was actually a $5 bill.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:14.850
It was just lying there
in the street.

00:49:14.850 --> 00:49:18.530
And so, I reached down to pick
it up, and then, suddenly, it

00:49:18.530 --> 00:49:19.610
disappeared.

00:49:19.610 --> 00:49:22.400
And it was people on one of the
stoops of one of these New

00:49:22.400 --> 00:49:25.820
York townhouses playing
a game.

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:28.250
They'd tied a string
to a $5 bill.

00:49:28.250 --> 00:49:31.240
And they would leave it on the
street, and watch people reach

00:49:31.240 --> 00:49:33.320
for it, and they'd
snatch it away.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:36.690
That's the only time in my life
I ever saw a $5 bill on

00:49:36.690 --> 00:49:37.980
the pavement.

00:49:37.980 --> 00:49:40.860
And so, it's a pretty good
assumption that, if you see

00:49:40.860 --> 00:49:43.040
one, it isn't real.

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:46.390
And that's all this is saying,
that if the option price

00:49:46.390 --> 00:49:50.150
didn't follow this formula,
something would be wrong.

00:49:50.150 --> 00:49:52.190
And so, it had better followed
this formula.

00:49:55.340 --> 00:49:58.160
Now, that is the basic
core option theory.

00:49:58.160 --> 00:50:02.460
Now, the interesting thing about
this theory is, I didn't

00:50:02.460 --> 00:50:07.190
use the probability of up and
the probability of down.

00:50:07.190 --> 00:50:10.330
So somebody says, wait a minute,
my whole intuition

00:50:10.330 --> 00:50:13.820
about options is: I'd buy
an option, because it

00:50:13.820 --> 00:50:16.330
might be in the money.

00:50:16.330 --> 00:50:20.150
When I was just describing this
here, this is $0.45, I

00:50:20.150 --> 00:50:22.110
said, that's not much,
because it probably

00:50:22.110 --> 00:50:26.240
won't exceed $25.00.

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:29.880
It's so far below it.

00:50:29.880 --> 00:50:34.100
So, it seems like the options
should really be fundamentally

00:50:34.100 --> 00:50:39.370
tied to the probability
of success.

00:50:39.370 --> 00:50:40.790
But it's not here at all.

00:50:40.790 --> 00:50:42.070
There's no probability in it.

00:50:42.070 --> 00:50:43.600
You saw me derive it.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:45.840
Was I tricking you?

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:48.310
Well, I wasn't.

00:50:48.310 --> 00:50:49.280
I don't play tricks.

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:50.740
This is absolutely right.

00:50:50.740 --> 00:50:54.130
You don't need to know the
probability that it's in the

00:50:54.130 --> 00:50:58.210
money to price an option,
because you can price it out

00:50:58.210 --> 00:51:02.930
of pure no-arbitrage
conditions.

00:51:02.930 --> 00:51:08.050
So, that leads me then to the
famous formula for options

00:51:08.050 --> 00:51:12.840
pricing, the Black-Scholes
Option Pricing Formula, which

00:51:12.840 --> 00:51:14.420
looks completely different
from that.

00:51:14.420 --> 00:51:20.490
But it's a kindred, because it
relies on the same theory.

00:51:20.490 --> 00:51:22.080
And there it is.

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:29.000
This was derived in the late
70's, or maybe the early 70's,

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:35.190
by Fisher Black, who was at MIT
at the time, I think, but

00:51:35.190 --> 00:51:45.130
later went to Goldman Sachs, and
Myron Scholes, who is now

00:51:45.130 --> 00:51:49.900
in San Francisco,
doing very well.

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:55.115
I see him at our Chicago
Mercantile Exchange meetings.

00:51:58.280 --> 00:51:59.695
Fisher Black passed away.

00:52:03.930 --> 00:52:06.220
It doesn't have the probability
that the option is

00:52:06.220 --> 00:52:09.460
in the money, either, but it
looks totally different from

00:52:09.460 --> 00:52:12.795
the formula that I
wrote over there.

00:52:12.795 --> 00:52:20.623
The call price is equal to the
share price, S, times N of d

00:52:20.623 --> 00:52:27.830
sub 1, where d sub 1 is this
equation, minus e to the minus

00:52:27.830 --> 00:52:32.380
r, the interest rate, times time
to maturity, T, times the

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:37.230
exercise price times N of d sub
2, where this is d sub 2.

00:52:37.230 --> 00:52:39.780
And the N function is the
cumulative normal

00:52:39.780 --> 00:52:41.676
distribution function.

00:52:41.676 --> 00:52:46.730
I'm not going to derive all
that, because it involves

00:52:46.730 --> 00:52:49.650
what's called the calculus
of variations.

00:52:49.650 --> 00:52:52.190
I don't think most of you
have learned that.

00:52:54.690 --> 00:52:58.360
In ordinary calculus, we have
what's called differentials,

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:01.380
dy, dx, et cetera.

00:53:01.380 --> 00:53:04.750
Those are fixed numbers
in ordinary calculus.

00:53:04.750 --> 00:53:09.620
In the mid 20th century,
mathematicians, notably the

00:53:09.620 --> 00:53:14.900
Japanese mathematician Ito,
developed a random version of

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:19.430
calculus, where dx and dy
are random variables.

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:22.130
That's called the stochastic
calculus.

00:53:22.130 --> 00:53:25.320
But I'm not going to use that.

00:53:25.320 --> 00:53:26.730
I'm not going to derive this.

00:53:26.730 --> 00:53:34.580
But you can see how to price an
option using Black-Scholes.

00:53:34.580 --> 00:53:39.460
But Black-Scholes is derived,
again, by the no-arbitrage

00:53:39.460 --> 00:53:42.210
condition and it doesn't
have the probability.

00:53:42.210 --> 00:53:45.180
Oh, the other variable that's
significant here is sigma,

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:49.290
which is the standard deviation
of the change in the

00:53:49.290 --> 00:53:51.050
stock price.

00:53:51.050 --> 00:53:53.930
So, once we put that in, someone
could say, well,

00:53:53.930 --> 00:53:58.410
probabilities are getting in
through the back door, because

00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:02.450
this is really a probability
weighted sum of the changes in

00:54:02.450 --> 00:54:04.510
stock prices.

00:54:04.510 --> 00:54:08.340
Well, probability is not really
in here at all, but

00:54:08.340 --> 00:54:11.340
maybe there's something like
standard deviation, even in

00:54:11.340 --> 00:54:12.850
this equation.

00:54:12.850 --> 00:54:15.410
Because we had C sub u and C sub
d, and that would give you

00:54:15.410 --> 00:54:16.276
some sense of the variability.

00:54:16.276 --> 00:54:16.332
[clarification: In the binomial
asset pricing model,

00:54:16.332 --> 00:54:16.428
u and d give you some sense
of the variability of the

00:54:16.428 --> 00:54:16.492
underlying stock price,
analogous to sigma in the

00:54:16.492 --> 00:54:17.742
Black-Scholes formula.]

00:54:20.770 --> 00:54:22.530
I'm going to leave this
equation just

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:25.270
for you to look at.

00:54:25.270 --> 00:54:31.080
But what it does do is, it shows
the option price as a

00:54:31.080 --> 00:54:33.350
nice curvilinear relationship,
just like the

00:54:33.350 --> 00:54:36.020
one I drew by hand.

00:54:36.020 --> 00:54:44.250
Which then, as time to exercise
goes down, as we get

00:54:44.250 --> 00:54:48.800
close to the exercise date,
that curve eventually

00:54:48.800 --> 00:54:51.090
coincides with the broken
straight line.

00:54:53.630 --> 00:55:01.060
Now, I wanted to tell you about
implied volatility.

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:04.950
This equation can be used
either of two ways.

00:55:04.950 --> 00:55:10.920
The most normal way to do it,
to use this equation, is to

00:55:10.920 --> 00:55:13.500
get the price that you think
is the right price for an

00:55:13.500 --> 00:55:16.650
option, to decide whether I'm
paying too much or too little

00:55:16.650 --> 00:55:18.770
for an option.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:22.850
So with this formula, I can
plug in all the numbers.

00:55:22.850 --> 00:55:26.620
To use this formula, I have to
know what the stock price is.

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:29.985
That's S. I have to know what
the exercise price is.

00:55:29.985 --> 00:55:32.180
And I have to know what the
time to maturity --

00:55:32.180 --> 00:55:35.900
these are all specified by the
stock price and the contract.

00:55:35.900 --> 00:55:38.110
I have to know with the
interest rate is.

00:55:38.110 --> 00:55:42.190
And if I also have some idea of
the standard deviation of

00:55:42.190 --> 00:55:46.940
the change in the stock
price, then I can

00:55:46.940 --> 00:55:49.700
get an option price.

00:55:49.700 --> 00:55:52.080
But I can also turn it around.

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:54.880
If I already know what the
option is selling for in the

00:55:54.880 --> 00:56:01.340
market, I can infer what the
implied sigma is, right?

00:56:01.340 --> 00:56:02.600
Because all the other
numbers in the

00:56:02.600 --> 00:56:04.770
Black-Scholes formula are clear.

00:56:04.770 --> 00:56:06.200
They're in the newspaper,
or they're

00:56:06.200 --> 00:56:08.210
in the option contract.

00:56:08.210 --> 00:56:12.030
There's this one hard to pin
down variable, what is the

00:56:12.030 --> 00:56:15.070
variability of the
stock price?

00:56:15.070 --> 00:56:18.950
And so, what people often use
the Black-Scholes formula to

00:56:18.950 --> 00:56:24.780
is, to invert it and calculate
the implied volatility of

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:26.090
stock prices.

00:56:26.090 --> 00:56:31.110
So, when call option prices are
high, why are they high

00:56:31.110 --> 00:56:33.150
relative to other times?

00:56:33.150 --> 00:56:35.240
Well, it must be that
people think --

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:37.700
I'm going back to the old
interpretation, that the

00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:40.530
probability of exercise
is high, right?

00:56:40.530 --> 00:56:43.510
If an out of the money call is
valuable, it must be people

00:56:43.510 --> 00:56:46.200
think that sigma is high.

00:56:46.200 --> 00:56:50.140
So, let's actually solve
for how high that is.

00:56:50.140 --> 00:56:53.190
I can't actually solve
this equation.

00:56:53.190 --> 00:56:54.740
I have to do it numerically.

00:56:54.740 --> 00:56:59.020
But I can calculate, for any
call price, given the stock

00:56:59.020 --> 00:57:02.830
price, exercise price, time to
maturity, and interest rate.

00:57:02.830 --> 00:57:08.590
I can calculate what volatility
would imply that

00:57:08.590 --> 00:57:10.100
stock price.

00:57:10.100 --> 00:57:16.820
And so, that's where we are
with Black-Scholes.

00:57:16.820 --> 00:57:24.670
So, implied volatility is the
options market's opinion as to

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:30.170
how variable the stock market
will be between now and the

00:57:30.170 --> 00:57:31.420
exercise date.

00:57:33.860 --> 00:57:38.850
So, one thing we can do is
compute implied volatility.

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:43.430
And I have that here
on this chart here.

00:57:43.430 --> 00:57:49.950
What I have here, from 1986 to
the present, with the blue

00:57:49.950 --> 00:58:00.570
line, is the VIX, V-I-X , which
is computed now by the

00:58:00.570 --> 00:58:03.660
Chicago Board Options
Exchange.

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:06.220
When the CBOE was founded,
they didn't

00:58:06.220 --> 00:58:07.800
know how to do this.

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:11.290
Black and Scholes invented their
equation in response to

00:58:11.290 --> 00:58:13.370
the founding of the CBOE.

00:58:13.370 --> 00:58:18.760
And now, the CBOE publishes
the VIX.

00:58:18.760 --> 00:58:21.010
And that's where I got this,
off their website cboe.com.

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:29.140
And so, they have computed,
based on the front month, the

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:35.520
near options, what the options
market thought the volatility

00:58:35.520 --> 00:58:37.100
of the stock market was.

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:39.590
That's the blue line.

00:58:39.590 --> 00:58:43.450
And you can see, it had a lot
of changes over time.

00:58:43.450 --> 00:58:47.020
That means that options prices
were revealing something about

00:58:47.020 --> 00:58:49.820
the volatility of the
stock market.

00:58:49.820 --> 00:58:51.890
Now, the blue line is
from the Chicago

00:58:51.890 --> 00:58:53.930
Board Options Exchange.

00:58:53.930 --> 00:58:59.190
What I did, and I calculated
this myself, the orange line

00:58:59.190 --> 00:59:05.360
is the standard deviation of
actual stock prices over the

00:59:05.360 --> 00:59:11.460
preceding year, of monthly
changes, annualized.

00:59:11.460 --> 00:59:13.640
That's actual volatility.

00:59:13.640 --> 00:59:17.490
But it's actual past
volatility.

00:59:17.490 --> 00:59:19.380
Let's make it clear,
what this is.

00:59:19.380 --> 00:59:26.080
What the VIX is, is the sigma in
the Black-Scholes equation.

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:32.890
But it is, in effect, the
market's expected standard

00:59:32.890 --> 00:59:34.620
deviation of stock prices.

00:59:34.620 --> 00:59:38.610
And to get it more precise, it's
the standard deviation of

00:59:38.610 --> 00:59:45.310
the S&amp;P 500 Stock Price Index
for one month, multiplied by

00:59:45.310 --> 00:59:49.110
the square root of 12, because
they want to annualize it.

00:59:49.110 --> 00:59:50.360
It's for the next month.

00:59:57.250 --> 00:59:59.420
Why do they multiply it by
the square root of 12?

00:59:59.420 --> 01:00:02.050
Well, that's because, remember
the square root rule.

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:04.520
These stock prices are
essentially independent of

01:00:04.520 --> 01:00:07.880
each other month to month, so
the standard deviation of the

01:00:07.880 --> 01:00:12.240
sum of 12 months is going to be
a square root of 12 times a

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:15.460
standard deviation
of one month.

01:00:15.460 --> 01:00:17.730
And this is in percent
per year.

01:00:17.730 --> 01:00:19.130
So, that means that the implied

01:00:19.130 --> 01:00:25.950
volatility in 1986 was 20%.

01:00:25.950 --> 01:00:31.840
And then, it shot way up to
60%, unimaginably quick.

01:00:31.840 --> 01:00:36.260
That might be the record high,
I can't quite tell from here.

01:00:36.260 --> 01:00:38.660
Remember, I told you the
story of the 1987

01:00:38.660 --> 01:00:40.290
stock market crash?

01:00:40.290 --> 01:00:43.260
The stock market fell
over 22% in one day.

01:00:43.260 --> 01:00:47.020
Well, actually, on the S&amp;P,
it was only 20%, but

01:00:47.020 --> 01:00:48.210
a lot in one day.

01:00:48.210 --> 01:00:50.800
It really spooked the
options markets.

01:00:50.800 --> 01:00:54.420
So, the call option prices went
way up, thinking that

01:00:54.420 --> 01:00:56.190
there's some big volatility
here.

01:00:56.190 --> 01:00:57.570
We don't know, which
way it'll be next.

01:00:57.570 --> 01:00:59.790
Maybe it will be up, maybe
it will be down.

01:00:59.790 --> 01:01:04.080
It pushed the implied
volatility, temporarily, up to

01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:05.400
a huge level.

01:01:05.400 --> 01:01:08.050
It came right back down.

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:12.610
My actual volatility, I
calculated this for each day

01:01:12.610 --> 01:01:14.290
as the volatility of
the market over

01:01:14.290 --> 01:01:16.070
the preceding year.

01:01:16.070 --> 01:01:21.130
Well, since I put October 1987
in my formula, I got a jump up

01:01:21.130 --> 01:01:26.110
in actual volatility, but not
at all as big as the options

01:01:26.110 --> 01:01:26.880
market did.

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:31.220
See, the option market is
looking ahead and I have no

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:35.850
way to look ahead, other than to
look at the options market.

01:01:35.850 --> 01:01:39.810
So, to get my actual volatility,
I was obliged to

01:01:39.810 --> 01:01:44.280
look at volatility in the past,
and it went up because

01:01:44.280 --> 01:01:47.350
of the 1987 volatility,
but not so much.

01:01:47.350 --> 01:01:50.490
So what this means is,
that, in 1987,

01:01:50.490 --> 01:01:52.320
people really panicked.

01:01:52.320 --> 01:01:54.380
They thought something
is really going on

01:01:54.380 --> 01:01:55.310
in the stock market.

01:01:55.310 --> 01:01:58.440
They didn't know what it was and
they were really worried,

01:01:58.440 --> 01:02:03.400
and that's why we see this spike
in implied volatility.

01:02:03.400 --> 01:02:06.290
There's a couple other spikes
that I've noted, the Asian

01:02:06.290 --> 01:02:10.610
financial crisis occurred
in the mid 1990's.

01:02:10.610 --> 01:02:16.900
Now, that is something that was
primarily Asian, but it

01:02:16.900 --> 01:02:19.720
got people anxious over
here as well.

01:02:19.720 --> 01:02:25.350
You know, Korea, Taiwan,
Indonesia, Hong Kong, these

01:02:25.350 --> 01:02:27.790
countries had huge turmoil.

01:02:27.790 --> 01:02:31.810
But it came over here in the
form of a sudden spike in

01:02:31.810 --> 01:02:33.360
expected volatility.

01:02:33.360 --> 01:02:36.130
People thought, things could
really happen here.

01:02:36.130 --> 01:02:40.500
So, all the option prices
got more valuable.

01:02:40.500 --> 01:02:41.770
And then there's this spike.

01:02:41.770 --> 01:02:43.800
This is the one that
you remember.

01:02:43.800 --> 01:02:46.850
This is the financial crisis
that occurred in

01:02:46.850 --> 01:02:48.610
the last few years.

01:02:48.610 --> 01:02:55.070
Notably, it peaks in the fall
of 2008, which was the real

01:02:55.070 --> 01:02:58.690
crisis, when Lehman Brothers
collapsed, and it created a

01:02:58.690 --> 01:03:01.090
crisis all over the world.

01:03:01.090 --> 01:03:05.510
There was a sharp and sudden
terrible event.

01:03:05.510 --> 01:03:10.410
And you can see, that actual
volatility shot up to the

01:03:10.410 --> 01:03:14.120
highest since 1986, as
well, at that time.

01:03:14.120 --> 01:03:20.320
So, implied volatility, you
can't ask easily from this

01:03:20.320 --> 01:03:22.620
chart, whether it was
right or wrong.

01:03:22.620 --> 01:03:27.260
People were responding to the
information, and the response

01:03:27.260 --> 01:03:29.205
felt its way into
options prices.

01:03:32.880 --> 01:03:35.520
There's no way to find out, ex
post, whether they were right

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:37.070
to be worried about that.

01:03:37.070 --> 01:03:44.500
But they were worried about
these events, and it led to

01:03:44.500 --> 01:03:47.110
big jumps in options prices.

01:03:47.110 --> 01:03:53.880
Now, I wanted to show the same
chart going back even further,

01:03:53.880 --> 01:03:57.370
but I can't do it with options
prices, because I can show

01:03:57.370 --> 01:04:01.710
volatility earlier, but I can't
