01:08:50.050 --> 01:08:55.470
Black-Scholes is not a
black swan theory.

01:08:55.470 --> 01:08:59.939
It assumes normality of
distributions, and so, it's

01:08:59.939 --> 01:09:01.320
not always reliable.

01:09:05.319 --> 01:09:11.149
So, this leads me to think that
option pricing theory --

01:09:11.149 --> 01:09:13.569
I presented a theory.

01:09:13.569 --> 01:09:18.250
The Black-Scholes theory is a
very elegant and very useful

01:09:18.250 --> 01:09:22.819
tool, especially useful when
things behave normally.

01:09:22.819 --> 01:09:25.439
But I think, one always has to
keep in the back of one's

01:09:25.439 --> 01:09:33.750
mind, the risk of sudden major
changes like we've seen here.

01:09:33.750 --> 01:09:35.710
So, let me just you
give us some final

01:09:35.710 --> 01:09:38.090
thoughts about options.

01:09:38.090 --> 01:09:39.850
I launched this lecture
by saying,

01:09:39.850 --> 01:09:42.040
they're very important.

01:09:42.040 --> 01:09:51.640
And they affect our lives
in many ways.

01:09:51.640 --> 01:09:55.520
I've been trying to campaign
for the expansion of our

01:09:55.520 --> 01:09:58.770
financial markets.

01:09:58.770 --> 01:10:03.050
Working with my colleagues and
the Chicago Mercantile

01:10:03.050 --> 01:10:08.260
Exchange, we launched options,
in 2006, on single-family

01:10:08.260 --> 01:10:10.640
homes in the United States.

01:10:10.640 --> 01:10:13.580
We were hoping that people
would buy put options to

01:10:13.580 --> 01:10:17.770
protect themselves against home
price declines, but the

01:10:17.770 --> 01:10:21.570
market never took off.

01:10:21.570 --> 01:10:25.270
We have, since, seen huge human
suffering because of the

01:10:25.270 --> 01:10:27.360
failure of people to
protect themselves

01:10:27.360 --> 01:10:29.170
against home price declines.

01:10:31.890 --> 01:10:36.700
There were various noises that
were made by people in power,

01:10:36.700 --> 01:10:39.840
that suggested that maybe
something could be done.

01:10:39.840 --> 01:10:43.190
President Obama proposed
something called Home Price

01:10:43.190 --> 01:10:46.750
Protection Program, and it
sounded like an option, a put

01:10:46.750 --> 01:10:48.160
option program.

01:10:48.160 --> 01:10:50.800
But, actually, it was a much
more subtle program than that.

01:10:50.800 --> 01:10:54.910
It was a program to incentivize
mortgage

01:10:54.910 --> 01:11:00.280
originators to do workouts on
mortgages, if the mortgages

01:11:00.280 --> 01:11:02.350
would default --

01:11:02.350 --> 01:11:03.880
if home prices were to fall.

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:05.430
And nothing really
happened with it.

01:11:05.430 --> 01:11:09.510
The President can't get things
started, either, not always.

01:11:09.510 --> 01:11:12.070
I've been proposing that
mortgages should have put

01:11:12.070 --> 01:11:14.510
options on the house
attached to them.

01:11:14.510 --> 01:11:17.410
When you buy a house, get
a mortgage, you should

01:11:17.410 --> 01:11:19.010
automatically get
a put option.

01:11:19.010 --> 01:11:21.270
I've got a new paper on that.

01:11:21.270 --> 01:11:23.000
But these are kind
of futuristic

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:24.250
things at the moment.

01:11:26.720 --> 01:11:30.340
I'm just saying this at the end,
just to try to impress on

01:11:30.340 --> 01:11:35.450
you, what I think is the real
importance of options markets.

01:11:35.450 --> 01:11:39.910
People don't manage risks well
in the present world.

01:11:39.910 --> 01:11:42.960
Having options or insurance-like
contracts of an

01:11:42.960 --> 01:11:46.910
expanded nature will help people
manage their risks

01:11:46.910 --> 01:11:51.770
better, and it will make
for a better world.

01:11:51.770 --> 01:11:53.830
OK.

01:11:53.830 --> 01:11:56.190
I'll see you on Monday.

